 World War II through the mid-1980s . The eradication of smallpox, the struggle to identify an effective polio vaccine, the unraveling of the secrets of Legionnaires' disease, and the shock over the identification of the HIV virus are all chronicled here. Drawing on hundreds of interviews and source documents, Etheridge vividly recreates the vital decision-making incidents that shaped both the growth of this institution as well as the state of public health in this country for the last five decades.We follow the development of the institution as it was transformed by the will and the imagination of remarkable individuals such as Dr. Joseph Mountin, one of the first heads of the CDC. Often characterized as abrasive and impatient, Mountin pushed the CDC to become a vital player in eradicating the threat of communicable disease in the United States. Others such as Dr. Alexander Langmuir brought the expertise necessary to establish epidemiology as one of the primary functions of the CDC.Created to serve the states and to answer any call for help whether routine or extraordinary, the CDC is now widely recognized as one of the world's premier public health institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEpidemiologyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aEpidemiology. 0aMedical personnel. 0aPublic health. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aamerican health.  aamerican politics.  acdc.  acenters for disease control.  acommunicable diseases.  adecision making.  adepartment of health and human services.  adisease control.  adisease prevention.  aenvironmental health.  aeradication.  afederal agency.  afirst world war.  afood borne pathogens.  ahealth promotion.  ahiv virus.  ainfectious diseases.  alegionnaires disease.  amalaria control unit.  anational public health institute.  aoccupational saf